<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-217-181 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 386 825</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Feb 25 1991 v37 n1849 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Interconnect densities in M/C modules heat station design.andO;(multi-chip modules can present thermal management problems forworkstation architects) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Levine, Bernard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer designers working with tightly packed multi-chip modulesare confounded by thermal management complications.andP;  Workstationtechnicians are considering several different packaging variationsto try to minimize the heat problem.andP;  Quad flat packs, solder bumpcarriers, and tab automated bonding are among the surface-mounttechniques sampled by board designers, who must deal with massiveinterconnect densities.andP;  The search for packaging alternatives hasalso led to investigation of non-traditional packaging techniquessuch as the use of high-speed, high-density connectors to mountsubstrates to workstation boards.andP;  Pin grid arrays have also beenconsidered, although cost and production delays are discouraging.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Boards/CardsIntegrated circuitsThermodynamicsPackaging.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   1990 worldwide package market. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>